         <div type="entry">
                <head>Timotheos II of Alexandria</head>
                <ab type="idnos">
                    <idno type="URI">https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Timotheos-II-of-Alexandria</idno>
                    <idno type="syriaca-bibl">http://syriaca.org/bibl/567</idno>
                    <idno type="entry">558</idno>
                    <milestone unit="pages" n="415-416"/>
                    <idno type="althead">Timothy Ailouros</idno>
                    <idno type="subject">http://syriaca.org/person/792</idno>
                    <note type="type">person</note>
                    <note type="abstract">Miaphysite <abbr>
                            <choice>
                                <sic>Patr.</sic>
                                <corr>patr.</corr>
                            </choice>
                    </abbr> of <placeName>Alexandria</placeName> 457-60, 475-7.<note/>
                    </note>
                </ab>
                <ab type="infobox">Timothy Ailouros (d. 477) [Miaphysite]</ab>
                <div type="body">
                    <p>Miaphysite <abbr>
                            <choice>
                                <sic>Patr.</sic>
                                <corr>patr.</corr>
                            </choice>
                        </abbr> of Alexandria 457–60, 475–7. His <choice>
                            <sic>nick-name</sic>
                            <corr>nickname</corr>
                        </choice> ‘Ailouros’, or
                        ‘weasel’, was due to his lean build. He attended the second Council of
                        Ephesus in 449, together with <abbr>Patr.</abbr> Dioscorus. After the lynching of the
                        pro-Chalcedonian <abbr>Patr.</abbr> Proterius in 457 he was made <abbr>
                            <choice>
                                <sic>Patr.</sic>
                                <corr>patr.</corr>
                            </choice>
                        </abbr> but was expelled
                        by the emperor in 460, eventually to be restored under Basiliscus. His
                        writings (<hi rend="italic">
                            <abbr>CPG</abbr>
                        </hi> 5475–5489), originally in Greek,
                        survive for the most part only in Syriac and Armenian. His major work, ‘On
                        the Unity of Christ’, against the Council of Chalcedon (<hi rend="italic">
                            <abbr>CPG</abbr>
                        </hi> 5475) is complete in Armenian (<abbr>ed.</abbr> K. Ter Mekerttschian and E.
                        Ter-Minassiantz, 1908; text only) but only in an abridged form in Syriac
                        (not yet fully published). Several of his letters and a refutation of
                        another work against the Chalcedonian Definition of Faith and the Tome of
                        Leo survive only in Syriac.</p>
                </div>
